00:50:59.460 --> 00:51:02.700
that inform you in terms
just the publishing process,

00:51:02.700 --> 00:51:05.960
or book touring, or, you
know, what sort of happens

00:51:05.960 --> 00:51:08.810
as your career stands spans more

00:51:08.810 --> 00:51:11.110
and more publications
in the years?

00:51:15.140 --> 00:51:16.440
&gt;&gt; Hieu Minh Nguyen:
One of the things

00:51:16.440 --> 00:51:23.030
that I have been learning, a
lesson that I keep with me,

00:51:23.030 --> 00:51:27.380
is that I don't have
to explain myself.

00:51:27.380 --> 00:51:31.460
I think like, you know,

00:51:32.740 --> 00:51:35.100
coming from all these
intersectional marginalized

00:51:35.100 --> 00:51:40.710
identities, like one of the
things that I felt the need

00:51:40.710 --> 00:51:42.870
to do is like defend myself.

00:51:42.870 --> 00:51:46.630
And, oftentimes, that looks
like explaining who I am

00:51:46.630 --> 00:51:50.780
and explaining, and it comes
with this idea that like

00:51:50.780 --> 00:51:58.360
if people know I am human
then they will accept me.

00:51:58.360 --> 00:52:05.630
But, then that's like also you
are pandering to these people

00:52:05.630 --> 00:52:08.680
who haven't treated you well
in the first place, right?

00:52:08.680 --> 00:52:12.040
Like, you're pandering to like
people in position of power

00:52:12.040 --> 00:52:16.400
and not just doing
the work, right?

00:52:16.400 --> 00:52:21.220
I think, -- so, yeah,
so like I am learning

00:52:21.220 --> 00:52:29.980
to like not feel the need
explain who I am and --

00:52:29.980 --> 00:52:33.200
I think we were talking
about it earlier,

00:52:33.200 --> 00:52:35.350
like asking for empathy, because
that's not what we're doing,

00:52:35.350 --> 00:52:36.650
right?

00:52:36.650 --> 00:52:37.950
That's not what we're --
I'm not asking for pity.

00:52:37.950 --> 00:52:46.970
I'm not asking to be considered.

00:52:50.510 --> 00:52:54.090
I'm just trying to make my own
space, if that makes sense.

00:52:54.090 --> 00:52:56.390
&gt;&gt; Gowri K.: Absolutely.

00:52:58.560 --> 00:53:00.740
&gt;&gt; R. O. Kwon: So,
with my first book,

00:53:00.740 --> 00:53:05.770
I spent the first two years
rewriting the first 20 pages

00:53:05.770 --> 00:53:08.040
over and over and over again
every day, the [inaudible].

00:53:08.040 --> 00:53:10.780
And then I threw it all away and
then I started all over again.

00:53:10.780 --> 00:53:12.840
So, I learned from
that to not do

00:53:12.840 --> 00:53:16.210
that [inaudible],
never, ever do that.

00:53:16.210 --> 00:53:17.510
I just -- I had this idea

00:53:17.510 --> 00:53:19.060
that I needed the
sentences to be perfect,

00:53:19.060 --> 00:53:20.480
to be exactly right.

00:53:20.480 --> 00:53:23.400
And I had this metaphor in
mind, and the metaphor was,

00:53:23.400 --> 00:53:26.490
you need a solid
foundation to build a house.

00:53:26.490 --> 00:53:29.020
And then, at the end of
those two years, belatedly,

00:53:29.020 --> 00:53:30.320
I realized it was
the worst metaphor,

00:53:30.320 --> 00:53:33.030
because you can't put -- you
can't put in a foundation

00:53:33.030 --> 00:53:34.410
if you don't know what
the house looks like.

00:53:34.410 --> 00:53:37.490
And, so -- and, so, with this
new book I've been trying --

00:53:37.490 --> 00:53:39.040
my new novel I've been trying,

00:53:39.040 --> 00:53:41.620
I've been working on
it for maybe two years,

00:53:41.620 --> 00:53:45.390
and I've been trying to speed
through as many drafts as I can

00:53:45.390 --> 00:53:48.970
to try to subvert my own
obsession with syllables,

00:53:48.970 --> 00:53:52.150
with language, with
punctuation, frankly.

00:53:52.150 --> 00:53:54.940
And I've been handwriting, I've
been doing all kinds of things

00:53:54.940 --> 00:53:56.760
to try to get through
it quickly.

00:53:56.760 --> 00:54:00.870
But, I don't -- I mean, the book
is such a -- it's such a like --

00:54:00.870 --> 00:54:02.170
it's just sort of a [inaudible]

00:54:02.170 --> 00:54:03.860
I have no idea what
it is and I feel

00:54:03.860 --> 00:54:05.160
as though I've forgotten
how to write.

00:54:05.160 --> 00:54:07.370
So, I'm not sure that
this method is any better.

00:54:07.370 --> 00:54:08.670
We'll see [laughter].

00:54:08.670 --> 00:54:11.040
[Inaudible] a while from now,
we'll see, like eight years.

00:54:11.040 --> 00:54:12.340
I don't know.

00:54:12.340 --> 00:54:13.640
I'm just hoping like six years,

00:54:13.640 --> 00:54:14.940
I'm hoping this book
will take six years.

00:54:14.940 --> 00:54:16.240
It sounds like a really nice,

00:54:16.240 --> 00:54:20.350
short winter [laughter]
compared to 10.

00:54:20.350 --> 00:54:26.280
In terms of what I -- one
thing I think I've learned,

00:54:26.280 --> 00:54:28.730
[inaudible] the other
day, I am not --

00:54:28.730 --> 00:54:32.060
I don't regret a single
thing I insisted for.

00:54:32.060 --> 00:54:34.040
I mean, I insisted
on for my book.

00:54:34.040 --> 00:54:37.370
I don't regret a single thing
I insisted on in terms of,

00:54:37.370 --> 00:54:40.040
I don't even know,
in terms of --

00:54:40.040 --> 00:54:44.130
in terms of like a single
mark or punctuation,

00:54:44.130 --> 00:54:49.630
in terms of never, ever tell
[inaudible] I mean Korean words

00:54:49.630 --> 00:54:52.540
or, you know, or French
words or anything.

00:54:52.540 --> 00:54:57.790
And I think I learned from that,
that people just aren't going

00:54:57.790 --> 00:55:00.040
to get as mad at me
as I think they will.

00:55:00.040 --> 00:55:01.750
I feel as though like
every time I insist

00:55:01.750 --> 00:55:04.830
on something I'm just worried
people will get incredibly

00:55:04.830 --> 00:55:06.360
offended and they'll
like cut off all --

00:55:06.360 --> 00:55:07.660
like I keep getting worried

00:55:07.660 --> 00:55:10.130
that people will cancel all the
contracts or like never want

00:55:10.130 --> 00:55:12.040
to talk to me again
or all these things.

00:55:12.040 --> 00:55:16.010
And nobody will ever, people
have said this and it's true,

00:55:16.010 --> 00:55:17.310
nobody cares about my book.

00:55:17.310 --> 00:55:19.220
Nobody ever cared
about my book as much

00:55:19.220 --> 00:55:21.720
as I did, not even my mother.

00:55:21.720 --> 00:55:25.240
And, so, [inaudible] more
of a consequence to me,

00:55:25.240 --> 00:55:28.350
which truly like there
are points when I said --

00:55:28.350 --> 00:55:30.430
when like -- when
like I've said things

00:55:30.430 --> 00:55:34.230
like I cannot change this
semi-colon to an em-dash,

00:55:34.230 --> 00:55:36.140
it would actually
ruin the integrity

00:55:36.140 --> 00:55:38.050
of the entire book
[laughter], [inaudible].

00:55:38.050 --> 00:55:42.540
And I felt that way and
I'm glad that I stuck

00:55:42.540 --> 00:55:45.730
by what I believed in,
even if I was afraid

00:55:45.730 --> 00:55:47.040
that everyone would
be mad at me.

00:55:47.040 --> 00:55:49.030
People just aren't going
to get that mad at you,

00:55:49.030 --> 00:55:52.260
I think is what -- is what
I took away, probably,

00:55:52.260 --> 00:55:55.430
I don't know, maybe,
who know [laughter].

00:55:55.430 --> 00:56:02.770
&gt;&gt; Gowri K.: I have you -- I
know, so dramatic [laughter].

00:56:02.770 --> 00:56:04.070
Stop the bus.

00:56:04.070 --> 00:56:07.860
I have another answer,
because you were talking

00:56:07.860 --> 00:56:10.070
about obsessions, right?

00:56:10.070 --> 00:56:12.150
And one of the things
that I learned

00:56:12.150 --> 00:56:16.130
when writing my second book,
right, is that like I had --

00:56:16.130 --> 00:56:19.960
I felt early on that I can't
write about the same things.

00:56:19.960 --> 00:56:23.360
I can't write about the same
subjects that I did in my --

00:56:23.360 --> 00:56:24.950
in my first book,
because like, you know,

00:56:24.950 --> 00:56:26.250
people want to hear
something else.

00:56:26.250 --> 00:56:28.110
People want to see
that I moved on, right?

00:56:28.110 --> 00:56:30.440
Like, so it's like learning

00:56:30.440 --> 00:56:32.600
that like your obsessions
can be your obsessions,

00:56:32.600 --> 00:56:34.640
that you can write about
the same thing forever.

00:56:34.640 --> 00:56:37.040
It's like okay, right?

00:56:37.040 --> 00:56:38.340
Like if you have --
like if you want to --

00:56:38.340 --> 00:56:41.240
if you want to write -- if I
want to write about this cup

00:56:41.240 --> 00:56:44.150
for the rest of my life, I'm
going to write about this cup.

00:56:44.150 --> 00:56:48.470
It's just like about like
how you approach it, right?

00:56:48.470 --> 00:56:53.600
And like -- yeah, but like
seeing things differently,

00:56:53.600 --> 00:56:56.250
and like that is also, yeah,

00:56:56.250 --> 00:56:58.490
obsessed over this
and it's okay.

00:56:58.490 --> 00:56:59.790
Yeah.

